The start symbol S can produce strings only via  

1. S → NT1 NT28  
2. S → NT50 NT27  

Hence the first token of any generated string must come from NT1 (rule 1) or NT50 (rule 2).

• NT50 is lexical: NT50 → 't4' | 't38'.  
  So if S uses rule 2, the first token would have to be t4 or t38, not t29.

• NT1 can derive
  – NT1 → 't69' | 't84' | 't28' | 't78' | 't5' | 't2' (all single terminals), or  
  – NT1 → NT25 NT17.

  None of the single-terminal alternatives give t29.  
  In the binary alternative the leftmost symbol is produced by NT25.  
  NT25 can be
     • NT25 → 't107'  (gives t107) or  
     • NT25 → NT6 NT31, whose leftmost terminal comes from NT6.  
       NT6 can yield only 't58', 't21', 't120', 't119', 't53', or 't81'.  

  Therefore no derivation from NT1 produces t29 as the first token.

Because the given string starts with t29, neither of the only two possible top-level derivations can match it, so the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

The start symbol S can expand only in one of two ways:

1. S → NT1 NT28  
2. S → NT50 NT27  

Case 2 requires the first token of the string to be produced by NT50.  
NT50 has only the productions  
 NT50 → 't4' | NT50 → 't38'  

Hence any string derived via Case 2 must begin with t4 or t38.  
Our string begins with t27, so Case 2 is impossible.

Case 1 requires the first token to be generated by NT1.  
The productions for NT1 are  

 NT1 → NT25 NT17  
 NT1 → 't69' | 't84' | 't28' | 't78' | 't5' | 't2'

Thus NT1 can begin a string with one of  
t69, t84, t28, t78, t5, t2, or whatever the first token produced by NT25 may be.

NT25 has productions  

 NT25 → NT6 NT31  
 NT25 → 't107'

So a string beginning with NT25 can start only with  
t107, or with the first token generated by NT6.

NT6’s productions are  

 NT6 → 't58' | 't21' | 't120' | 't119' | NT54 NT6

and NT54 → 't53' or 't81', so any string produced by NT6 starts with  
t58, t21, t120, t119, t53, or t81.

Collecting all possibilities, any string derivable via Case 1 must start with one of  
t69, t84, t28, t78, t5, t2, t107, t58, t21, t120, t119, t53, or t81.

The given string starts with t27, which is not among these possibilities.

Since neither Case 1 nor Case 2 can yield a string whose first token is t27, the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

To belong to the language, the first token of the string must be produced by the first non-terminal in one of the two start-rules:

1. S → NT1 NT28  
2. S → NT50 NT27  

Token 1 is t41.

• NT50 produces only the terminals t4 or t38 – never t41.  
• NT1 can be either a single terminal (t69, t84, t28, t78, t5, t2) or the concatenation NT25 NT17.  
 – NT25 is either the single terminal t107 or NT6 NT31.  
  • NT6 can yield the terminals t58, t120, t21, t119 (or start with NT54, which in turn yields t53 or t81).  
  • None of these possibilities gives t41 as the first symbol.  

Hence neither NT1 nor NT50 can generate the first token t41, making it impossible for S to derive the given string.

Therefore the string is not in the language.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT1 NT28  
2. S → NT50 NT27  

For S → NT50 NT27 to work, the left child NT50 must generate the first part of the string.  
However NT50 has only the two terminal productions   
 NT50 → 't4' or NT50 → 't38'  
so it can contribute at most a single token – but our string does not begin with either t4 or t38.  
Hence the derivation S → NT50 NT27 is impossible.

The only remaining possibility is S → NT1 NT28, so the 34‑token string must be split into  
some prefix generated by NT1 and a suffix generated by NT28.

NT28, however, is extremely restricted.  Its productions are

 NT28 → NT4 NT6  
 NT28 → NT8 NT8  
 NT28 → 't76'  
 NT28 → 't97'

Consequences:

• If NT28 → 't76' or NT28 → 't97', the entire suffix would be a single token (t76 or t97).  
  Our string does not end with either of these tokens.

• If NT28 → NT8 NT8, the suffix would have to be exactly the two‑token sequence  
  t102 t102 (because NT8 → 't102').  The given string does not contain “… t102 t102” at its end.

• The only remaining choice is NT28 → NT4 NT6.  
  In that case NT6 must generate the final part of the string.  
  But NT6 is defined by

 NT6 → 't58' | 't120' | 't21' | 't119' | NT54 NT6  with NT54 → 't53' | 't81'

  Therefore every string in L(NT6) consists of zero or more occurrences of t53 or t81
  followed by exactly one of {t58, t120, t21, t119}.  
  Looking at the tail of the target string, we read it backwards until we meet a token
  that is not t53, t81, t58, t120, t21, or t119:

  … t120 t42 t87 t21   ← the t42 breaks the required pattern

  Hence it is impossible to choose a contiguous suffix of the string that matches the shape required by NT6, so NT28 → NT4 NT6 cannot generate the end of the string either.

Since no production for NT28 can cover the final portion of the given 34‑token string, the derivation S → NT1 NT28 is impossible, and we have already ruled out S → NT50 NT27.

Therefore the grammar cannot generate the supplied string.
